  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Qualification is the narrowing or limiting of a claim to make it more precise, more defensible, and more honest. \u0026ldquo;Social media causes depression\u0026rdquo; is an unqualified claim. \u0026ldquo;Certain social media features — particularly algorithmic content feeds — correlate with increased depressive symptoms in adolescents aged 13–17, according to three longitudinal studies\u0026rdquo; is a qualified claim. The second is less dramatic and more credible.\nQualification is not weakness. It is precision. An unqualified claim invites the reader to find the one counterexample that disproves it — and once they find it, the entire argument loses credibility. A qualified claim has already acknowledged its limits, which paradoxically makes it stronger: the reader trusts a writer who knows the boundaries of their evidence.\n",
  "name": "Qualification",
